HTML - browser turns tags into elements in a tree (DOM)
    <tag>
    content - empty, text, or other element
    </tag>

    <h1 class = "article">
    Udacity
    </h1>

CSS - uses a specific syntax & rules to change how elements look on the page

p {

}
^ in css this will apply a style to all paragraphs

.description {

}
^ this will apply the style to anything in the class "description"

placehold.it -- makes fast images to work with the dimensions on the website
<img src="http://placehold.it/100x100">

to make things disappear:
@media only screen and (max-width: 500px) {
  p {
      display: none;
  }
}

HTML Lists:
<ul> </ul> -- stands for unordered list (no numbers), creates a list with bold bullet points
<ol> </ol> -- ordered list, numbered list
<li> </li> -- stands for list item, need these inside ul and ol

Images:
<img src="URL" alt="Explanation">

Adding CSS:
In between the head tags, you can insert a tag
<style>
  h2 {
    color: rgb(0, 232, 15); -- may or may not bring up a color picker
  }
  body {
    background-color: rgb(97, 250, 255);
  }
</style>
